From: Eli Barzilay <eli@barzilay.org>
To: Robby Findler <robby@cs.uchicago.edu>
Cc: Matthew Flatt <mflatt@cs.utah.edu>, matthias@ccs.neu.edu,
        bugs@plt-scheme.org
Subject: Re: all/7140: Bug report server used by Help Desk appears to be down
Date: Fri, 17 Dec 2004 22:03:45 -0500

 On Dec 17, Robby Findler wrote:
 > At Fri, 17 Dec 2004 19:45:14 -0700, Matthew Flatt wrote:
 > > At Fri, 17 Dec 2004 20:43:12 -0600, Robby Findler wrote:
 > > > What had we decided to do before? IIRC, we were going to use
 > > > port 80 on bugs.plt-scheme.org and render bad answers as html?
 > > > Has the email tunnel been set up there yet?
 > > 
 > > As I recall, we were going to HTTP (on port 80) instead of SMTP.
 
 Yes.
 
 
 > I thought we were going to use SMTP on port 80. I guess we can make
 > up some kind of XML format, but I thought earlier that you had found
 > it easier to make a simple tunnel? Maybe the security concerns make
 > it worth it now?
 
 SMTP on 80 would be close to impossible.  You'll need some server
 process that will wait for input and guess whether it should go to a
 web server or to SMTP...
 
 I don't remember what your reply was, but I think that the most sane
 approach would be to simply use the same bugs.plt-scheme.org page in
 help-desk.  It should ideally behave in exactly the same way, except
 for some value auto-filling that help-desk will do.  The bug report I
 just filed was done this way, so it seems to work, a little ugly and
 hard to fill in help-desk (eg, tab does not jump to the next field).
 
 If you can hack this to work fine, then the current system will be
 fine as it is, and the advantage is that it is easy to change the html
 page on the server when the fields are modified.  Also, if people have
 problems with proxies, web redirections etc, they'll see the rendered
 result.
 
 -- 
           ((lambda (x) (x x)) (lambda (x) (x x)))          Eli Barzilay:
                   http://www.barzilay.org/                 Maze is Life!
