Date: Fri, 17 Dec 2004 22:18:18 -0500

 On Dec 17, Robby Findler wrote:
 > The GUI frontend is not broken, so we shouldn't fix it. Using forms
 > in Help Desk's browser is going to be much crappier than what we
 > have.
 
 OK.  You lose the ability to customize it remotely, but that's all.
 (The 299 help-desk does not render the submittion form, it just says
 "stopped".)
 
 (Another idea is -- have the bug report dialog connect to some page on
 bugs.plt-scheme.org which will list fileds and types, and the dialog
 will be filled according to that.  Shouldn't be too hard since there
 is only one column of fields.)
 
 
 > The protocol for the communication (once the user submits the bug
 > report) is completely up for grabs, tho. Anything you want there is fine.
 
 Well, POST will be the easiest.  If you use the same field names, then
 you could send the data to the same place that bugs.plt-scheme.org
 goes, which is bugs.plt-scheme.org/cgi-bin/bug-report -- a script that
 Paul wrote that uses sendmail to submit the bugs.  Then there will be
 double benefit from any hacking on that script.
 
 Again, this functionality is there now, so you can do that without any
 changes on the server.
 
 
 On Dec 17, Robby Findler wrote:
 > Do proxies generally allow POST?
 
 They should, or you'd be aware of using a proxy since you won't be
 able to use such forms...
 
 -- 
