Subject: Re: all/7140: Bug report server used by Help Desk appears to be down
Date: Sat, 18 Dec 2004 00:14:21 -0500

 On Dec 17, Robby Findler wrote:
 > Well, I guess whoever does it can do it however, but one way would
 > be to move the code that generates the email to the server (ie, it
 > listens for a post that contains an email message to whereever the
 > email is currently going and actually just sends it out).
 
 No no -- you definitely don't want to do that.  There is a trivial
 perl script called `formmail' that will simply send any data to some
 specified email, which can be used as an easy solution for collecting
 data: you simply put the html page up and have a form with your
 formmail.pl as its action and it'll send it to you.  It turned out to
 be a security problem -- most http logs will have plenty of bad
 references to this thing that hackers and viruses use.
 
 
 > I think that I will wait for someone to make a server (and the spec)
 > and I'll make the bug report form send according to that spec.
 
 What I'm trying to say is that it's already there...  It is the same
 script, bugs.plt-scheme.org/cgi-bin/bug-report, that handles bug
 submissions.  You need to send that page POST data that contains the
 fields.
 
 I will post an input example soon, right after I finish the 209
 release.
 
