Subject: Re: all/7140: Bug report server used by Help Desk appears to be down
Date: Sun, 19 Dec 2004 00:03:45 -0500

 On Dec 18, Robby Findler wrote:
 > At Sat, 18 Dec 2004 23:36:48 -0500, Eli Barzilay wrote:
 > > * If there was an error, the error page says "<Click here> to
 > >   submit a new report".  Can you add a bogus "help-desk" argument
 > >   that will be set to "true", and I'll make the script say "Click
 > >   XXX below to try to edit your bug report".
 > 
 > What kind of error are you talking about?
 
 The cgi-script will try to catch all errors that occur when it sends
 the email, and if it happens it shows a different result page.  I now
 added a (+ 12 "34") after sending the email so you should see that
 result when you submit a bug.
 
 
 > > * Related to the above -- the "XXX" would currently be "reset".  I
 > >   think that a better label would be "back", or "re-submit", or
 > >   "restart".
 > 
 > What is XXX?
 
 The label on the button you get after submitting the bug, which goes
 back to the bug dialog.
 
 
 On Dec 18, Robby Findler wrote:
 > At Sat, 18 Dec 2004 23:36:48 -0500, Eli Barzilay wrote:
 > > * Related to the above -- the "XXX" would currently be "reset".  I
 > >   think that a better label would be "back", or "re-submit", or
 > >   "restart".
 > 
 > Oh, I think I know what you are talking about now.
 > 
 > re-submit isn't good because it doesn't actually submit anything. I
 > don't like restart because it already has an overloaded meaning for
 > computers. Back is kind of okay, but doesn't really mean what the
 > back button means in browsers.
 > 
 > Any other words?
 
 Well, I share your objectsions to re-submit and to "restart".  "back"
 seems to make the most sense because it is sort of like going back in
 a browser -- if someday there is enough support to render an html
 form properly, then it will actually be a simple "back".
 
 The reason I don't like "reset" is that I thought that it would reset
 the whole thing and remove information -- my natural reaction was to
 hesitate to click it since I thought that the information will be
 deleted...  With a "back" label I (as a browser user) would expect the
 exact behavior that happens.
 
